* {{Cite magazine |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=January 12, 2024 |title=Taylor Swift and Miley Cyrus Reign Over Australia's End Of Year Charts |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/taylor-swift-miley-cyrus-reign-australias-2023-end-of-year-charts-1235580552/ |access-date=February 7, 2024 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=January 19, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240119094106/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/taylor-swift-miley-cyrus-reign-australias-2023-end-of-year-charts-1235580552/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and ranked as the second best-performing song of the year on the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 2023|''Billboard'' year-end Hot 100 chart of 2023]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=November 21, 2023 |title=Morgan Wallen Is the No. 1 Billboard Hot 100 Artist of 2023 & 'Last Night' Is Top Song |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/morgan-wallen-top-billboard-hot-100-artist-2023-last-night-top-song-1235491475/ |access-date=February 7, 2024 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=November 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231121181611/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/morgan-wallen-top-billboard-hot-100-artist-2023-last-night-top-song-1235491475/ |url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI), it was the [[List of best-selling singles#Best-selling singles by year worldwide|best-selling song of 2023]] globally.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=February 26, 2024 |title=Miley Cyrus' 'Flowers' Wins IFPI Global Single Award For 2023 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/miley-cyrus-flowers-ifpi-global-single-award-2023-1235614759/ |access-date=February 26, 2024 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=February 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240226153802/https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/miley-cyrus-flowers-ifpi-global-single-award-2023-1235614759/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A demo version of the track followed on March 3, 2023.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Rowley |first=Glenn |date=March 3, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Drops Demo Version of 'Flowers': Stream It Now |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/miley-cyrus-flowers-demo-version-stream-it-now-1235279005/ |access-date=March 8, 2023 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230303054819/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/miley-cyrus-flowers-demo-version-stream-it-now-1235279005/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Cyrus's eighth studio album, ''[[Endless Summer Vacation]]'', was released on March 10, 2023. She co-produced it with [[Kid Harpoon]], [[Greg Kurstin]], Mike Will Made It, and [[Tyler Johnson (musician)|Tyler Johnson]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Dailey |first=Hannah |date=January 5, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Announces New Album 'Endless Summer Vacation': Here's When It Arrives |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-new-album-release-date-announced-1235194508/ |magazine=Billboard |access-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105153627/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-new-album-release-date-announced-1235194508/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Cyrus announced the album in January, with its artwork and a trailer.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Irvin |first=Jack |date=January 5, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Announces New Album 'Endless Summer Vacation' — Her 'Love Letter' to Los Angeles |url=https://people.com/music/miley-cyrus-announces-new-album-endless-summer-vacation-release-date/ |access-date=January 5, 2023 |magazine=People |archive-date=January 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230117150900/https://people.com/music/miley-cyrus-announces-new-album-endless-summer-vacation-release-date/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Her first studio effort with Columbia Records, she described the record as "[her] love letter to LA", which reflects upon the "strength [she] found in focusing on [her] physical and mental well-being".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Garcia |first=Thania |date=January 5, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus to Release New Album 'Endless Summer Vacation' in March, Drops Teaser Trailer |url=https://variety.com/2023/music/news/miley-cyrus-endless-summer-new-album-march-1235479750/ |access-date=January 5, 2023 |magazine=Variety |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105173417/https://variety.com/2023/music/news/miley-cyrus-endless-summer-new-album-march-1235479750/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The album, a pop and [[dance-pop]] record,<ref>
* {{Cite news |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |author-link=Alexis Petridis |date=March 10, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus: ''Endless Summer Vacation'' review – gossip, grit and glorious pop |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/mar/10/miley-cyrus-endless-summer-vacation-review |access-date=June 12, 2024 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}
* {{Cite magazine |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=March 10, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Spends Her 'Endless Summer Vacation' Deftly Balancing Mellow Gold and Dance-Pop: Album Review |url=https://variety.com/2023/music/album-reviews/miley-cyrus-endless-summer-vacation-album-review-1235549124/ |access-date=June 11, 2024 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> features collaborations with [[Brandi Carlile]] and [[Sia]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |date=February 27, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Reveals 'Endless Summer Vacation' Tracklist Featuring Two Surprise Collabs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/miley-cyrus-endless-summer-vacation-tracklist-features-1235261261/ |access-date=February 27, 2023 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=February 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230228082251/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/miley-cyrus-endless-summer-vacation-tracklist-features-1235261261/ |url-status=live }}</ref> It debuted at number three on the US ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 119,000 album-equivalent units. It marked Cyrus's tenth top-five and fourteenth top-ten entry on the chart.<ref name="BB200">{{cite magazine |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |date=March 19, 2023 |title=Morgan Wallen Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 With 'One Thing at a Time' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/morgan-wallen-one-thing-at-a-time-second-week-number-one-billboard-200-1235289396/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=March 20, 2023 |archive-date=March 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319203115/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/morgan-wallen-one-thing-at-a-time-second-week-number-one-billboard-200-1235289396/ |url-status=live }}</ref> "[[River (Miley Cyrus song)|River]]", the second single off the record, was released on March 13, 2023.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Rowley |first=Glenn |date=March 10, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Drops 'River' Music Video |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/miley-cyrus-river-music-video-1235283216/ |access-date=March 28, 2023 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=March 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230310134150/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/miley-cyrus-river-music-video-1235283216/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=March 14, 2023 |title=A recap of radio add recaps |url=https://hitsdailydouble.com/news%26id%3D335107 |access-date=February 7, 2024 |magazine=[[Hits (magazine)|Hits]] |archive-date=January 10, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240110164405/https://hitsdailydouble.com/news%26id%3D335107 |url-status=live }}</ref> It debuted at number 32 on the US Hot 100 and reached number two on the [[Dance/Electronic Songs|Hot Dance/Electronic Songs]] chart.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Murray |first=Gordon |date=March 23, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus' 'River' Flows Onto Hot Dance/Electronic Songs Chart |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/miley-cyrus-river-hot-dance-electronic-songs-chart-debut/ |url-access=subscription |access-date=March 28, 2023 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=March 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230328224328/https://www.billboard.com/pro/miley-cyrus-river-hot-dance-electronic-songs-chart-debut/ |url-status=live }}</ref> "[[Jaded (Miley Cyrus song)|Jaded]]", which peaked at number 56, was released as the third single on April 17, 2023.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Pilley |first=Max |date=May 18, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus shares new video for 'Jaded' |url=https://diymag.com/news/miley-cyrus-shares-new-video-for-jaded |access-date=February 8, 2024 |magazine=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |archive-date=March 3, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240303194136/https://diymag.com/news/miley-cyrus-shares-new-video-for-jaded |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Bowenbank |first=Starr |date=March 27, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Thanks Fans for 'Flowers' 8th Week at No. 1, Drops 'Jaded' Backyard Session |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-flowers-8th-week-no-1-jaded-backyard-sessions-watch-1235293486/ |access-date=May 25, 2023 |magazine=Billboard |quote="Jaded" is currently at No. 56 on the chart. |archive-date=May 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230525124142/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-flowers-8th-week-no-1-jaded-backyard-sessions-watch-1235293486/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-drops-jaded-video-1234736412/|title=Miley Cyrus Strips Down in the Dreamy 'Jaded' Video|last=Mier|first=Tomás|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 16, 2023|access-date=May 18, 2023|archive-date=June 8, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608114712/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-drops-jaded-video-1234736412/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Endless Summer Vacation'' was the 19th best-selling album of 2023 globally, according to IFPI.<ref>{{Cite web |date=February 27, 2024 |title=SEVENTEEN's FML announced by IFPI as biggest-selling Global Album of the Year |url=https://ifpi.fi/uutiset/2024/02/seventeens-fml-announced-by-ifpi-as-biggest-selling-global-album-of-the-year/ |access-date=May 9, 2024 |publisher=[[Musiikkituottajat]] |agency=IFPI Finland |archive-date=May 9, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240509094949/https://ifpi.fi/uutiset/2024/02/seventeens-fml-announced-by-ifpi-as-biggest-selling-global-album-of-the-year/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

A documentary concert special, under her [[Backyard Sessions]] series, titled ''Endless Summer Vacation (Backyard Sessions)'', premiered on [[Disney+]] on March 10, accompanying the album's release.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Blistein |first=Jon |date=March 3, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Reviving the 'Backyard Sessions' for 'Endless Summer Vacation' Special |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-backyard-sessions-endless-summer-vacation-1234690323/ |access-date=March 5, 2023 |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-date=March 30, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230330061309/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-backyard-sessions-endless-summer-vacation-1234690323/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Executive produced by Cyrus, it features her performing songs from the album, and her 2009 single "[[The Climb (song)|The Climb]]", with an appearance by [[Rufus Wainwright]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=March 3, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus and Disney Reunite for 'Endless Summer Vacation (Backyard Sessions)' |url=https://variety.com/2023/music/news/miley-cyrus-disney-endless-summer-vacation-backyard-sessions-1235542234/ |access-date=March 5, 2023 |website=Variety |archive-date=March 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230304171259/https://variety.com/2023/music/news/miley-cyrus-disney-endless-summer-vacation-backyard-sessions-1235542234/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Paul |first=Larisha |date=March 10, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus Needs No Audience or Introduction in 'Endless Summer Vacation' Special |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/miley-cyrus-disney-plus-endless-summer-vacation-backyard-sessions-reaction-1234693915/ |access-date=March 18, 2023 |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-date=March 11, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311000810/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/miley-cyrus-disney-plus-endless-summer-vacation-backyard-sessions-reaction-1234693915/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In June, she guest-voiced Van in the second season of the Netflix [[adult animated]] sitcom, ''[[Human Resources (TV series)|Human Resources]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=June 8, 2023 |title=See Miley Cyrus Like You've Never Seen Her Before |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-news/human-resources-netflix-miley-cyrus-never-seen-her-animation-1234766200/ |access-date=June 10, 2023 |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-date=June 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230609172522/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-news/human-resources-netflix-miley-cyrus-never-seen-her-animation-1234766200/ |url-status=live }}</ref> An updated version of the Disney+ special, titled ''Endless Summer Vacation: Continued (Backyard Sessions)'', premiered on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on August 24, 2023. The day after, Cyrus released the single "[[Used to Be Young]]", which was included in the digital reissue of ''Endless Summer Vacation''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Petski |first=Denise |date=August 17, 2023 |title=Miley Cyrus To Release New Song "Used To Be Young" With ABC Special |url=https://deadline.com/2023/08/miley-cyrus-song-used-to-be-young-release-abc-special-1235521683/ |magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=August 17, 2023 |archive-date=August 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230824064055/https://deadline.com/2023/08/miley-cyrus-song-used-to-be-young-release-abc-special-1235521683/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The track debuted at number eight in the US.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=September 5, 2023 |title=Zach Bryan & Kacey Musgraves' 'I Remember Everything' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/zach-bryan-i-remember-everything-hot-100-number-one-debut-1235405939/ |access-date=February 7, 2024 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=September 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230905144226/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/zach-bryan-i-remember-everything-hot-100-number-one-debut-1235405939/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 20, [[Dolly Parton]] released a rock re-recording of "Wrecking Ball" featuring Cyrus as a guest vocalist, as the final single off her studio album ''[[Rockstar (Dolly Parton album)|Rockstar]]'' (2023).<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Aniftos |first=Rania |date=October 20, 2023 |title=Dolly Parton Reveals Why She Included 'Wrecking Ball' on Upcoming 'Rockstar' Album: 'I Love My Miley' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/dolly-parton-miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-rockstar-album-1235449764/ |magazine=Billboard |access-date=February 7, 2024 |archive-date=November 2, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231102205556/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/dolly-parton-miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-rockstar-album-1235449764/ |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Billboard'' ranked Cyrus as the ninth-best-selling musician of 2023.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date= |title=2023 Year-End Charts: Top Artists |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/top-artists/ |access-date=March 1, 2024 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=February 3, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240203043206/https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/top-artists/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

At the [[66th Annual Grammy Awards]], Cyrus received six nominations, including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]] for ''Endless Summer Vacation'', and won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] for "Flowers"—her first set of wins.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last1=Garcia |first1=Thania |last2=Murphy |first2=J. Kim |date=February 4, 2024 |title=Miley Cyrus Wins Her First Grammys Ever for 'Flowers' |url=https://variety.com/2024/music/news/miley-cyrus-wins-first-grammy-flowers-1235892230/ |access-date=February 9, 2024 |magazine=Variety |archive-date=February 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240206192337/https://variety.com/2024/music/news/miley-cyrus-wins-first-grammy-flowers-1235892230/ |url-status=live }}</ref> She appeared in a cameo role as Tiffany Plastercaster—inspired by [[Cynthia Plaster Caster]]—in the [[Ethan Coen]]-directed comedy road film ''[[Drive-Away Dolls]]'', released later that month.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Saperstein |first=Pat |date=February 23, 2024 |title=Who Was Cynthia Plaster Caster, Who Inspired Miley Cyrus' Character in Ethan Coen's 'Drive Away Dolls'? |url=https://variety.com/2024/film/news/who-was-cynthia-plaster-caster-miley-cyrus-drive-away-dolls-1235920770/ |access-date=February 25, 2024 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-date=February 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240226044606/https://variety.com/2024/film/news/who-was-cynthia-plaster-caster-miley-cyrus-drive-away-dolls-1235920770/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Her first release of 2024 was as a feature on "[[Doctor (Work It Out)]]" by [[Pharrell Williams]]. The song is an outtake from her fourth album ''[[Bangerz]]'' (2013); it was leaked online in 2017 and was reworked and re-recorded before being released on March 1, 2024.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Paul |first=Larisha |date=March 1, 2024 |title=Miley Cyrus and Pharrell Reunite For First Time in a Decade on 'Doctor (Work It Out)' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-pharrell-williams-doctor-work-it-out-1234978403/ |access-date=March 1, 2024 |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-date=March 1, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240301065418/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-pharrell-williams-doctor-work-it-out-1234978403/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Cyrus was also featured on the duet "[[II Most Wanted]]" from [[Beyoncé]]'s album ''[[Cowboy Carter]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Viswanath |first=Jake |date=March 28, 2024 |title=Beyoncé & Miley Cyrus' Duet "II Most Wanted" Is A True Ride-Or-Die Anthem |url=https://www.bustle.com/entertainment/beyonce-miley-cyrus-ii-most-wanted-lyrics-meaning-explained |access-date=March 28, 2024 |magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |archive-date=March 29, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240329062653/https://www.bustle.com/entertainment/beyonce-miley-cyrus-ii-most-wanted-lyrics-meaning-explained |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Brathwaite |first=Lester Fabian |date=March 28, 2024 |title=Beyoncé's Cowboy Carter features a Miley duet, a Beatles cover, and cameos from Dolly Parton and Willie Nelson|url=https://ew.com/beyonce-cowboy-carter-has-dolly-parton-willie-nelson-miley-cyrus-beatles-remake-8621612 |access-date=March 28, 2024 |magazine=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> The song was released as the album's third single in April 2024,<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=April 2, 2024 |title=A Recap of Radio Add Recaps |url=https://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=340537&title=A-RECAP-OF-RADIO-ADD-RECAPS |access-date=April 19, 2024 |magazine=[[Hits (magazine)|Hits]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Farrell |first=David |date=April 8, 2024 |title=Hozier, Beyoncé & Miley Cyrus, The Beaches Have This Week's Hot New Radio Tracks in Canada |url=https://ca.billboard.com/business/radio/hozier-beyonce-miley-cyrus-the-beaches-have-this-week-s-hot-new-radio-tracks |access-date=April 19, 2024 |magazine=[[Billboard Canada]]}}</ref> and reached the top ten in the US, the UK, and on the Global 200.<ref>
* {{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=April 8, 2024 |title=Future, Metro Boomin & Kendrick Lamar Hold Atop Hot 100, Beyoncé Boasts Three in Top 10 |url=https://www.billboard.com/lists/future-metro-boomin-kendrick-lamar-like-that-hot-100-number-one-second-week/ |access-date=April 19, 2024 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}
* {{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=April 8, 2024 |title=Benson Boone's 'Beautiful Things' Leads Global Charts, Beyoncé, Artemas & ILLIT Hit Top 10 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/benson-boone-beyonce-artemas-illit-global-charts-1235651713/ |access-date=April 19, 2024 |magazine=Billboard}}
* {{Cite magazine |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=April 8, 2024 |title=Beyonce's 'Texas Hold 'Em' Rebounds to No. 1 In U.K. |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/beyonce-texas-hold-em-rebounds-no-1-uk-1235651215/ |access-date=April 19, 2024 |magazine=Billboard}}</ref> As one of 16 acts featured on the [[Talking Heads]] tribute album ''[[Everyone's Getting Involved: A Tribute to Talking Heads' Stop Making Sense]]'', Cyrus provided a synth-driven dance-pop rendition of the band's "[[Psycho Killer]]". The album was released on May 17, 2024, by [[A24 Music]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/miley-cyrus-talking-heads-psycho-killer-cover-1235022798/|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|title=Hear Miley Cyrus' Edgy Cover of Talking Heads' 'Psycho Killer'|date=May 17, 2024|access-date=May 23, 2024|first=Emily|last=Zembler}}</ref>
